INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7cbd02dd-71fb-464a-b6c6-df335b6493ae',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte Component Design — Splitting Logic from Presentation with the 150-Line Rule$escape$,
  $escape$Svelte's single-file format makes it tempting to pile reactive declarations, fetch calls, and markup into one `.svelte` file. Resist it.

The 150-line rule is a practical heuristic: if your file exceeds it, you have multiple responsibilities tangled together. Split aggressively.

Presentation components own zero state beyond transient UI state (open/closed, hovered). They receive data via `export let` props and communicate up via `createEventDispatcher`. No `fetch`, no store writes, no `onMount` side effects—purely declarative.

Logic lives elsewhere: SvelteKit's `load()` functions own route data fetching, `writable`/`derived` stores own shared mutable state, and plain `.ts` modules own pure computation. A `userStore.ts` exporting a `derived` readable is far more testable than a component juggling both concerns.

The tell: if your `<script>` block imports multiple stores, dispatches events, *and* runs `onMount` side effects, it's coordinating too much. Extract that orchestration into a parent container or store, leaving leaf components purely presentational.

Reactive declarations (`$:`) inside a presentation component should only derive display values from props—never trigger network calls or mutate external stores.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- UserCard.svelte — presentation only -->
<script lang="ts">
  import { createEventDispatcher } from 'svelte';
  import type { User } from '$lib/types';

  export let user: User;
  export let loading = false;

  const dispatch = createEventDispatcher<{ follow: string }>();
  $: label = user.isFollowed ? 'Unfollow' : 'Follow';
</script>

{#if loading}<span>Loading…</span>
{:else}
  <article>
    <h2>{user.name}</h2>
    <button on:click={() => dispatch('follow', user.id)}>{label}</button>
  </article>
{/if}$escape$,
