INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c659c458-659e-4ebc-959e-a7c0751e0761',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte State Management — Local, Lifted, Context, and Stores$escape$,
  $escape$Svelte gives you four distinct layers for state, each with a clear use case. Use `let` for component-local state — it's reactive by default, no boilerplate needed. When a child needs to mutate parent state, lift it up and pass a callback or use `bind:value` for two-way binding, but keep this shallow — deep binding chains become brittle fast.

For cross-tree sharing without prop-drilling, `setContext`/`getContext` scopes state to a component subtree. It's synchronous and non-reactive on its own — pair it with a `writable` store to make it reactive. Crucially, context is per-component-instance, not global, so it's safe for things like a modal's internal state tree.

For truly global, reactive, shared state — user session, theme, cart — reach for Svelte stores: `writable`, `readable`, or `derived`. Subscribe with the `$` prefix in templates for automatic cleanup. `derived` is underused: it computes values from other stores lazily, replacing selectors you'd write manually in Redux. Avoid stores for ephemeral UI state — that's what `let` is for.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- stores.ts -->
import { writable, derived } from 'svelte/store';

export const cart = writable<Item[]>([]);
export const cartCount = derived(cart, $cart => $cart.length);

<!-- Cart.svelte -->
<script>
  import { cart, cartCount } from './stores';
</script>

<p>{$cartCount} items</p>
<button on:click={() => cart.update(c => [...c, newItem])}>Add</button>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
