INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9b7bdef4-4748-4eba-a41f-65afef785ed8',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte 5 — Prop Typing with Discriminated Unions for Variant Components$escape$,
  $escape$Svelte 5's `$props()` rune works seamlessly with TypeScript interfaces, giving you full type safety at the component boundary. For variant-style components — buttons, alerts, badges — discriminated unions eliminate the `any` escape hatch and make illegal states unrepresentable.

Define a union type where a shared `variant` literal field acts as the discriminant. TypeScript narrows the type automatically based on which variant is passed, so a `destructive` button can require a `confirmLabel` prop that a `default` button never needs. No runtime checks required — the compiler enforces it.

In Svelte 5, declare props with `let { variant, ...rest }: ButtonProps = $props()`. The destructuring is typed end-to-end: the parent gets a compile error if it passes a prop invalid for the selected variant. Avoid `type Props = { variant: string; label?: string }` — that's just a typed `any`. Use the union, let the discriminant do the work, and keep your component API honest.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- Button.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  type DefaultProps = { variant: 'default'; label: string };
  type DestructiveProps = { variant: 'destructive'; label: string; confirmLabel: string };
  type ButtonProps = DefaultProps | DestructiveProps;

  let props: ButtonProps = $props();
</script>

{#if props.variant === 'destructive'}
  <button>{props.label} — confirm: {props.confirmLabel}</button>
{:else}
  <button>{props.label}</button>
{/if}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
