INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ee0678a2-eedb-4b43-9424-5f5652a54b4d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte Error Handling — Route Boundaries, Loading, and Empty States$escape$,
  $escape$SvelteKit gives you per-route error boundaries via `+error.svelte` files. Drop one next to any `+page.svelte` and it catches errors thrown during `load` for that route and its children. Use the `error()` helper from `@sveltejs/kit` to throw typed HTTP errors — it sets both status and message, which `$page.error` and `$page.status` expose in your error page.

For loading states during client-side navigation, `$navigating` from `$app/stores` is your signal — it's non-null while a route transition is in flight. Avoid client-side `{#await}` for data that belongs in `load`; keep async work server-side so the page renders with resolved data.

Empty states live in `+page.svelte` itself. Since `load` returns typed data, a null or empty array check is straightforward — no ambiguity with loading state because SvelteKit serializes the distinction. Nest `+error.svelte` deeper in the route tree to scope error UI: an error in `src/routes/posts/[slug]/+page.ts` won't bubble to the root boundary if `posts/+error.svelte` exists.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/routes/posts/[slug]/+page.ts
import { error } from '@sveltejs/kit';

export async function load({ params, fetch }) {
  const res = await fetch(`/api/posts/${params.slug}`);
  if (!res.ok) error(res.status, { message: 'Post not found' });
  const post = await res.json();
  if (!post) error(404, { message: 'Post is empty' });
  return { post };
}

// src/routes/posts/+error.svelte
<script>
  import { page } from '$app/stores';
</script>
<h1>{$page.status} — {$page.error?.message}</h1>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
