INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7cb281d4-af9a-4f64-8772-bf1bbe2911be',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte Accessibility — Semantic HTML First, ARIA Only When HTML Falls Short$escape$,
  $escape$Svelte's compiler warns you about missing ARIA attributes, but the real goal is avoiding ARIA entirely by reaching for native HTML first. A `<button>` beats `<div role="button">` every time — it's focusable, keyboard-operable, and announced correctly without a single line of JS.

For focus management, use Svelte's `bind:this` to capture DOM references and call `.focus()` imperatively after state transitions — e.g., returning focus to a trigger element when a modal closes. Wire this into `onMount` or reactive `$effect` blocks so it runs after the DOM settles.

Svelte 5's `$effect` is cleaner than `afterUpdate` for this: it runs post-DOM-commit and tracks dependencies automatically. Combine with `tick()` when you need to wait for a conditional block to render before focusing.

Use `aria-live="polite"` on dynamic regions (toast notifications, search results) where routing or reactive state swaps content the screen reader won't otherwise detect. Keep ARIA scoped — one `aria-live` region per concern, not a global wrapper.$escape$,
  $escape$<script>
  import { tick } from 'svelte';

  let dialogOpen = $state(false);
  let triggerRef = $state(null);
  let dialogRef = $state(null);

  async function openDialog() {
    dialogOpen = true;
    await tick();
    dialogRef?.focus();
  }

  function closeDialog() {
    dialogOpen = false;
    triggerRef?.focus(); // return focus to trigger
  }
</script>

<button bind:this={triggerRef} onclick={openDialog}>Open</button>

{#if dialogOpen}
  <dialog bind:this={dialogRef} open aria-modal="true" aria-label="Settings">
    <button onclick={closeDialog}>Close</button>
  </dialog>
{/if}

<div aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">
  {#if dialogOpen}Dialog is open{/if}
</div>$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
