INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '85bda351-a0bd-4d8b-af23-e6d82d26a8d8',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte i18n — Never Hardcode Strings, Use svelte-i18n and the Intl API$escape$,
  $escape$Hardcoding strings in Svelte components is a maintenance trap—reach for `svelte-i18n` instead. It exposes a `$_` store that you import and call reactively; every locale switch triggers a re-render automatically because it's just a Svelte writable store under the hood.

Setup: call `register` and `init` once in your root `+layout.ts`, pointing to locale JSON files. Then in any component, `$_('key.path')` returns the translated string. Interpolation is `$_('greeting', { values: { name } })`.

For dates and numbers, skip library wrappers and drive `Intl.NumberFormat` and `Intl.DateTimeFormat` directly off `svelte-i18n`'s `$locale` store. A reactive declaration `$: formatter = new Intl.NumberFormat($locale, { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD' })` rebuilds whenever the locale changes—currency, percent, and compact notation are free. Same pattern for `Intl.DateTimeFormat` with `dateStyle: 'medium'`.

The key insight: `$_` and `$locale` are plain Svelte stores. Reactivity is automatic—no React context, no HOCs, no provider wrapping. Just subscribe with `$` and let the compiler handle the rest.$escape$,
  $escape$<script lang="ts">
  import { _, locale } from 'svelte-i18n';

  let price = 49.99;
  let date = new Date();

  $: currencyFormatter = new Intl.NumberFormat($locale, {
    style: 'currency',
    currency: 'USD'
  });

  $: dateFormatter = new Intl.DateTimeFormat($locale, {
    dateStyle: 'medium'
  });
</script>

<h1>{$_('welcome.title')}</h1>
<p>{$_('item.price', { values: { name: 'Pro Plan' } })}</p>
<p>{currencyFormatter.format(price)}</p>
<p>{dateFormatter.format(date)}</p>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
