INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '025e5b5f-c896-4e17-afb6-c1a0b1470056',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SvelteKit Env Vars — Validate with Zod at Startup, Never at Runtime$escape$,
  $escape$SvelteKit exposes environment variables through dedicated modules: `$env/static/private` for build-time server secrets, `$env/dynamic/private` for runtime server vars, and their `public` counterparts (prefixed with `PUBLIC_`) for client-safe values. Never reach for `process.env` directly — SvelteKit's module system enforces access boundaries and enables tree-shaking.

The weak point is silent failures: a missing `DATABASE_URL` won't crash until the first DB query. Fix this by validating all vars at startup with Zod. Create `src/lib/server/env.ts`, parse `$env/dynamic/private` through a Zod schema, and throw on failure. Then import that module in `hooks.server.ts` — SvelteKit runs this file before any request is handled, so misconfiguration surfaces immediately on boot, not in production at 3 AM.

Use `z.coerce.number()` for numeric vars (PORT, timeouts) since env values are always strings. Use `.default()` for optional config with sane fallbacks. Export the typed `config` object and import it wherever you need env values — no more scattered `env.DATABASE_URL` calls with silent `undefined` bugs.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/lib/server/env.ts
import { z } from 'zod';
import { env } from '$env/dynamic/private';

const schema = z.object({
  DATABASE_URL: z.string().url(),
  GROQ_API_KEY: z.string().min(1),
  PORT: z.coerce.number().positive().default(3000),
});

const result = schema.safeParse(env);
if (!result.success) throw new Error(result.error.toString());
export const config = result.data;

// src/hooks.server.ts
import '$lib/server/env'; // validates on boot, crashes fast if misconfigured$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
