INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '343dff21-cdd5-4b42-b70d-d4c8bb973303',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Svelte Quality Gates — Prettier, Husky + lint-staged, and tsc --noEmit in CI$escape$,
  $escape$Svelte projects need quality gates tuned to their toolchain. Prettier handles `.svelte` files via `prettier-plugin-svelte` — without it, the formatter mangles `<script>`, markup, and `<style>` blocks. Add it to your Prettier config and set `parser: 'svelte'` for `.svelte` overrides.

Husky + lint-staged runs checks only on staged files. Wire `svelte-check` (not just `tsc`) into lint-staged — it catches type errors inside `<script lang="ts">` blocks that plain `tsc` misses because `.svelte` files aren't TypeScript modules. Your `lint-staged` config should run `prettier --write` then `svelte-check --tsconfig ./tsconfig.json` on `*.svelte` patterns.

In CI, `tsc --noEmit` validates your non-Svelte TypeScript (utils, stores, hooks), while a separate `svelte-check` step covers component types. Splitting them gives clearer failure signals. Run both in parallel to keep pipelines fast. Skip `svelte-check` on the local hook if it's slow — gate it in CI only and use `--threshold error` to allow warnings without failing the build.$escape$,
  $escape$// lint-staged.config.js
export default {
  '*.{ts,js}': ['prettier --write', 'eslint --fix'],
  '*.svelte': [
    'prettier --write --plugin prettier-plugin-svelte',
    () => 'svelte-check --tsconfig ./tsconfig.json --threshold error'
  ]
}

// .prettierrc
{
  "plugins": ["prettier-plugin-svelte"],
  "overrides": [{ "files": "*.svelte", "options": { "parser": "svelte" } }]
}$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
